{"id":"2101.03619","submitter":"Antonio Macchia","authors":"Davide Bolognini, Antonio Macchia, Francesco Strazzanti","title":"Cohen-Macaulay binomial edge ideals and accessible graphs","comments":"accepted in Journal of Algebraic Combinatorics","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1007/s10801-021-01088-w","report-no":null,"categories":"math.AC math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The cut sets of a graph are special sets of vertices whose removal\ndisconnects the graph. They are fundamental in the study of binomial edge\nideals, since they encode their minimal primary decomposition. We introduce the\nclass of accessible graphs as the graphs with unmixed binomial edge ideal and\nwhose cut sets form an accessible set system. We prove that the graphs whose\nbinomial edge ideal is Cohen-Macaulay are accessible and we conjecture that the\nconverse holds. We settle the conjecture for large classes of graphs, including\nchordal and traceable graphs, providing a purely combinatorial description of\nCohen-Macaulayness. The key idea in the proof is to show that both properties\nare equivalent to a further combinatorial condition, which we call strong\nunmixedness.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 10 Jan 2021 20:06:43 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 3 Jan 2022 10:54:22 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-01-04"}
